{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"192e1f90-4e5e-4349-9865-c999669610a1","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Action | Events fired |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created` → `Activated` |\n| User switches away | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` |\n| User returns | `Resumed` → `Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` → `Destroying` |\n\n> **Note:** `Backgrounding` is iOS/Mac Catalyst only — use it to save state before the OS may terminate your app. On Android/Windows it won't fire.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ff5402d9-221c-4e70-ac9e-4929ed69d6ba","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI, not a codebase-specific task. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":427,"requestId":"981C:155537:168EF9C:191BFB1:6A051E77"},"id":"a3c9c086-03bf-483f-b9de-3d9910fd5364","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:59:44.314Z","parentId":"91bfe70d-033a-4743-a91e-47e3a59219c0"}
